==Trivia==
{{toomuchtrivia}}
*The band members picked the name R.E.M. out of the dictionary. They liked the name because it was so ambiguous and was easy to write on posters and put on buttons.<ref>iTunes Originals interview, 2004</ref> They started out as Twisted Kites for the first show they played at a party, but, according to ''It crawled from the South'', they considered Negro Eyes, Slut Bank, and Cans of Piss before settling for R.E.M.
*According to one boxed set of their albums, R.E.M. stands for Rapid Ear Movement, a play on [[Rapid Eye Movement]].
* In 1980, R.E.M. supported [[The Police]] on tour. This relationship was most likely setup through [[Ian Copeland]] who acted as booking agent for both bands. Ian Copelands's older brother [[Miles Copeland III]] founded [[I.R.S. Records]] (R.E.M's record label at the time), and younger brother [[Stewart Copeland]] was the drummer for The Police.
* In 1982, R.E.M. was the first band to play Chicago's [[Metro Chicago|Metro]].
* In 2001, R.E.M appeared in an episode of [[The Simpsons]] called "[[Homer the Moe]]", as themselves.
* R.E.M. re-wrote "[[Shiny Happy People]]" for their guest appearance in ''[[Sesame Street]]''. It was re-named "Furry Happy Monsters" and features Buck, Mills and Stipe playing amid a group of Muppets.
* Disappointed with the results of his lip-synching in the band's first video, "Wolves, Lower", Michael Stipe vowed never to lip-synch in a video again. He performed vocals live for all of R.E.M.'s videos until 1991's "Losing My Religion". He changed his mind after watching [[Sin<U+00E9>ad O'Connor]] video for "[[Nothing Compares 2 U]]". Stipe has lip-synched in the video for the lead single from each album since.
*When ''Rolling Stone'' named R.E.M. "America's Best Band" in November 1987, drummer Bill Berry said, "We're not the best rock 'n' roll band in America." [[Pylon (band)|Pylon]], he said, was the best.
* In 1996, the entire band excluding Mike Mills cowrote "Slapstick Heart" for [[Sam Phillips (singer)|Sam Phillips]]' album ''[[Omnipop (It's Only A Flesh Wound Lambchop)]]''.
* In response to R.E.M.'s release of ''[[Green (album)|Green]]'', Chicago-based band [[Green (band)|Green]] released a CD entitled ''R.E.M.''
*R.E.M.'s album ''[[Green (album)|Green]]'' was referenced in the episode 'Animals R Us' of the TV show ''[[Northern Exposure]]''. ([[Maggie O'Connell|Maggie O'Connell's]] late boyfriend is said to have been accustomed to listening to the album and singing along with it after dinner each night.)

